  "doc_id": "16631",
  "text": "Expression of constitutively active Rac1, a member of the Rho family of small GTPases, potentiates the activity of the H. pylori VacA toxin in two different epithelial cell lines (SCC12F keratinocytes and MDCK cells) [CITATION_1] . Furthermore, pinocytosis of VacA is regulated by the Cdc42 GTPase in HeLa and gastric AGS cells [CITATION_2] . Hence, we postulated that the same mechanism may be utilized in macrophages and that the H. pylori VacA toxin is involved in the immune-inhibitory effect observed. Indeed, the addition of H. pylori vacA mutant and VacA-containing supernatant from wildtype H. pylori 251 to L. acidophilus-stimulated BMDMs showed that VacA is essential for the inhibition of IFN-␤ responses.",
